{  
  "response_text": "The plot shows fluctuations in the count of E-RO strategy households across 100 timesteps. Initial values (steps 0-15) cluster between 25 and 35 households. A sharp decline occurs in most lines around step 10-15, consistent with a catastrophe event triggered by pasture biomass falling below 75 (resulting in 25% population loss). Post-catastrophe trajectories vary:   - Lines with fastest recovery (e.g., gray) stabilize between 20-25 households after ~15 steps   - Faster-declining lines (orange, pink) approach 5-10 households by step 30   - Slower-moving lines (green, cyan) maintain 15-20 households throughout execution. Sustained declines suggest E-RO struggles in prolonged drought phases (rain-mean=200 ±100 volatility). Recovery plateaus near 0.8–1.2 cattle per household suggest equilibrium grazing capacity. No line recovers to initial values, indicating non-learning strategies fail to adapt to climatic stress under fixed parameters. The plot confirms catastrophic thresholds and grazing mismanagement consequences in E-RO populations."
}

